Goal of This Exercise
You learn how to:
1.	Remove project creation permission from normal users
2.	Create groups
3.	Add users to groups
4.	Create a project
5.	Assign project administrator
6.	Give developer write access
7.	Give QA read-only access
This simulates a real company structure.
Example company structure:
Role	Permissions
Admin	manage cluster
Leader	manage project
Developers	deploy apps
QA	only view
________________________________________
Step 1: Start the Lab Environment
Command:
lab start auth-rbac
Purpose:
•	prepares the OpenShift cluster
•	ensures required users and resources exist
________________________________________
Step 2: Login as Cluster Administrator
oc login -u admin -p redhatocp https://api.ocp4.example.com:6443
Explanation:
•	oc login → authenticate to cluster
•	admin → cluster administrator
•	redhatocp → password
Only cluster administrators can modify cluster-level RBAC.
________________________________________
Step 3: Find Who Can Create Projects
Command:
oc get clusterrolebinding -o wide | grep -E 'ROLE|self-provisioner'
Example output:
self-provisioners ClusterRole/self-provisioner system:authenticated:oauth
Meaning:
ClusterRoleBinding: self-provisioners
Role: self-provisioner
Group: system:authenticated:oauth
________________________________________
What is self-provisioner?
self-provisioner role allows users to create projects.
Example command users can run:
oc new-project myproject
________________________________________
system:authenticated:oauth Group
This is a virtual group.
It contains:
all authenticated users
Meaning:
everyone who logs in
So by default:
ALL users can create projects
________________________________________
Step 4: Verify the Role Binding
Command:
oc describe clusterrolebindings self-provisioners
Output shows:
Role: self-provisioner
Group: system:authenticated:oauth
Meaning:
All logged-in users can create projects
________________________________________
Step 5: Remove Project Creation Privilege
Command:
oc adm policy remove-cluster-role-from-group \
self-provisioner system:authenticated:oauth
Explanation:
Remove role → self-provisioner
From group → system:authenticated:oauth
Result:
normal users cannot create projects anymore
Only cluster admins can create projects now.
________________________________________
Step 6: Verify Role Binding Removed
Command:
oc describe clusterrolebindings self-provisioners
Expected output:
NotFound
Meaning:
role binding deleted successfully
________________________________________
Step 7: Confirm No Other Binding Exists
Command:
oc get clusterrolebinding -o wide | grep -E 'ROLE|self-provisioner'
Expected result:
no results
So:
self-provisioner role no longer assigned
________________________________________
Step 8: Test With Normal User
Login as leader:
oc login -u leader -p redhat
Try creating project:
oc new-project test
Result:
Error: Forbidden
Meaning:
leader cannot create project
RBAC working correctly.
________________________________________
Step 9: Admin Creates Project
Login again as admin:
oc login -u admin -p redhatocp
Create project:
oc new-project auth-rbac
Meaning:
create namespace/project called auth-rbac
________________________________________
Step 10: Assign Project Administrator
Command:
oc policy add-role-to-user admin leader
Explanation:
Role: admin
User: leader
Project: auth-rbac
Meaning:
leader becomes project administrator
Leader can now:
manage deployments
add roles
manage users
But only inside auth-rbac project.
________________________________________
Step 11: Create Developer Group
Command:
oc adm groups new dev-group
Meaning:
create group called dev-group
________________________________________
Step 12: Add Developer to Group
Command:
oc adm groups add-users dev-group developer
Meaning:
dev-group
   └ developer
________________________________________
Step 13: Create QA Group
Command:
oc adm groups new qa-group
________________________________________
Step 14: Add QA User
oc adm groups add-users qa-group qa-engineer
Group structure now:
dev-group
   └ developer

qa-group
   └ qa-engineer
________________________________________
Step 15: Verify Groups
Command:
oc get groups
Example output:
dev-group     developer
qa-group      qa-engineer
________________________________________
Step 16: Leader Assigns Permissions
Login as leader:
oc login -u leader -p redhat
Leader is project admin, so can assign roles.
________________________________________
Step 17: Give Developers Write Access
Command:
oc policy add-role-to-group edit dev-group
Explanation:
Role: edit
Group: dev-group
Project: auth-rbac
Meaning:
developers can create apps
developers can modify deployments
developers can delete resources
________________________________________
Step 18: Give QA Read Access
Command:
oc policy add-role-to-group view qa-group
Meaning:
QA can only view resources
Cannot:
create
modify
delete
________________________________________
Step 19: Verify Role Bindings
Command:
oc get rolebindings -o wide
Example output:
admin     ClusterRole/admin   leader
edit      ClusterRole/edit    dev-group
view      ClusterRole/view    qa-group
Meaning:
Role	Assigned To
admin	leader
edit	dev-group
view	qa-group
________________________________________
Step 20: Test Developer Permissions
Login as developer:
oc login -u developer -p developer
Deploy application:
oc new-app --name httpd \
registry.ocp4.example.com:8443/rhscl/httpd-24-rhel7
Explanation:
creates deployment
creates service
deploys Apache HTTP Server
This works because developer has edit role.
________________________________________
Step 21: Test Admin Privileges
Developer tries:
oc policy add-role-to-user edit qa-engineer
Result:
Forbidden
Meaning:
developer cannot manage permissions
Because edit role cannot manage RBAC.
Only admin role can.
________________________________________
Step 22: Test QA Permissions
Login as QA user:
oc login -u qa-engineer -p redhat
Try scaling deployment:
oc scale deployment httpd --replicas 3
Result:
Forbidden
Because QA has view role only.
QA can only run commands like:
oc get pods
oc get services
oc describe deployment
________________________________________
Step 23: Restore Default Behavior
Login as admin:
oc login -u admin -p redhatocp
Restore project creation permission:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-group \
--rolebinding-name self-provisioners \
self-provisioner system:authenticated:oauth
Meaning:
all authenticated users can create projects again
________________________________________
Final RBAC Structure
Cluster
 │
 ├ admin
 │
Project: auth-rbac
 │
 ├ leader → admin role
 │
 ├ dev-group → edit role
 │     └ developer
 │
 └ qa-group → view role
       └ qa-engineer
________________________________________
Key Commands to Remember (EX280 Important)
Remove project creation
oc adm policy remove-cluster-role-from-group
________________________________________
Restore project creation
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-group
________________________________________
Create group
oc adm groups new group-name
________________________________________
Add user to group
oc adm groups add-users group-name user
________________________________________
Assign role to user
oc policy add-role-to-user role user
________________________________________
Assign role to group
oc policy add-role-to-group role group
________________________________________
Real-World Architecture
Companies use this structure:
Cluster Admins
    │
Project Admin (team lead)
    │
Developers → edit role
QA → view role
This provides secure multi-team collaboration.

